snippet.textDisplay: Best thing you can do to transfer over to a plant-based diet is the 5 and 2 method.  Go five consecutive days plant-based and two days whatever you want.  Eventually you will find that those five days you stick to plant-based foods...you will be more efficient in physical activities, cognitive endeavors, and more restful sleep.  It's simply a life changer.   The hardest part is memory transference.  You remember BBQ's and you remember meals with your family etc...the smells and the flavors.  It takes a while to supplant those memories with great plant-based meals with friends and family.  A year or more really.  But, it's worth it.  Later in life, you will make fewer trips to the doctor and live longer.  People will argue the opposite.  But, they are simply incorrect.

snippet.textDisplay:
As far as tackling the cement issue, look up the technology that a company call BioMason is pursuing. They use bacteria to bind aggregates substrates together.
Apparently all it requires is mixing the bacteria culture with the aggregates and feeding them Urea while they are saturated in a Calcium Chloride solution. They then use the energy in the Urea and the calcium ion in the solution to build a calcium carbonate shell/crystals, which will then bind things like sand together within a few days. This is suppose to be quite similar to how Coral reefs form and they are using this technology to produce bricks that do not require high heat processing of calcium carbonate.

Mark, I expected a more scientific approach from you. To supplement this, I'd like to call for 2 things:
1. A double blind experiment to see if the groups could distinguish between animal meat and plant-based meat
2. A comparison of nutrition - Calories, Protein, Carbs, Fat, Saturated Fat, vitamins, and Sodium between the two burgers
3. I don't think it makes for a good video, but a review of the degree of processing for each of the options. Plant-based meats seem highly processed especially looking at how one was made in this video. Although, whether that's a good or bad thing is a completely different question.


Unfortunately, I understand that I am biased. Waiting for cost effective, lab-grown animal meat to replace the factory farmed animal meat.

snippet.textDisplay: While I can admit to them making great strides in the last few years, there is still one minor problem... every single example shown has been composed of a generally homogeneous mix of ground up products.... whether they are animal based or vegetable is irrelevant as they are both ground up to the same consistency... and even stuffed into a "casing" for those sausages... They have not, nor will they be able to reproduce any of the "long grain" stranding of muscle fibers and/or tissues for sometime to come, which is the rock they will continue to break upon .  These advances can lead to a fairly decent reduction of direct demand, but let's also remember that burgers and sausages were oft times originally made with the "leftover" bits of meat that were too small to sell and cast off/ thrown out as not worth the effort. If plant based ingredients take over this "niche" then are we to go back to "wasting" or composting these unwanted/ unsalable bits?  There is always much more to the story then the mere surface you are scratching at here.
